    <title>Meta fed its AI on almost everything you’ve posted publicly since 2007</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Meta logo on a red background with repeating black icons, giving a squiggly effect." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Pmq_VQ3Zf3kUFgRcUj7Dx20i1Es=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73581260/STK043_VRG_Illo_N_Barclay_3_Meta.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Illustration by Nick Barclay / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="vXg9nb"&gt;Meta has acknowledged that all text and photos that adult Facebook and Instagram users have publicly published since 2007 have been fed into its artificial intelligence models. &lt;a href="https://www.abc.net.au/news/2024-09-11/facebook-scraping-photos-data-no-opt-out/104336170"&gt;Australia’s &lt;em&gt;ABC News&lt;/em&gt; reports&lt;/a&gt; that Meta’s global privacy director, Melinda Claybaugh, initially rejected claims about user data from 2007 being leveraged for AI training during a local government inquiry about AI adoption before relenting after additional questioning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="hfxNPG"&gt;“The truth of the matter is that unless you have consciously set those posts to private since 2007, Meta has just decided that you will scrape all of the photos and all of the texts from every public post on Instagram or Facebook since 2007 unless there was a conscious decision to set them on...&lt;/p&gt;
