    <title>iFixit made its own USB-C soldering iron, and it’s already a joy</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A hand holds up a soldering iron connected to a battery, with a red ring of light around the iron signaling that it’s hot and a 360 degree temperature indicator on the battery’s screen." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Ix2xkF5fdyOcTLVv6Xf88H1DErk=/99x0:3339x2160/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73580879/DJI_20240911084604_0192_D.0.jpeg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;The iFixit portable soldering station.&lt;/em&gt; | Photo by Sean Hollister / The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="TXAJDq"&gt;My first USB-C soldering iron was a revelation. “You mean I can make liquid metal connections &lt;em&gt;anywhere&lt;/em&gt;, in &lt;em&gt;seconds&lt;/em&gt;, just by plugging this tiny stick into a USB cable?” Now, repair company iFixit is introducing &lt;a href="https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;amp;xs=1&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ifixit.com%2FNews%2F99434%2Fintroducing-fixhub-the-portable-soldering-system&amp;amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F2024%2F9%2F12%2F24242497%2Fifixit-fixhub-usb-soldering-iron-station-battery-toolkit-price-release-date" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;its own take on the idea&lt;/a&gt;. It claims the iFixit FixHub Smart Soldering Iron is powerful enough for pros and easier for beginners than any others that have come before. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="HJuqzk"&gt;So far, it’s not a &lt;em&gt;new&lt;/em&gt; revelation, but after my first couple of hours, I’m loving iFixit’s improvements on an already great idea.&lt;/p&gt;
